<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900926-0085</DOCNO><DOCID>900926-0085.</DOCID><HL>   Dividend News:   American Brands Inc.   Declares 2-for-1 Split   And Increases Payout</HL><DATE>09/26/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18</SO><CO>   AMB</CO><IN>TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)DIVIDENDS (DIV)</IN><LP>   OLD GREENWICH, Conn. -- American Brands Inc. said itdeclared a 2-for-1 stock split on its common shares andincreased its quarterly dividend on the post-split stock by13%.   The additional shares from the split will be distributedOct. 25 to stockholders of record Oct. 9, the company said.After the split, about 197 million shares will beoutstanding. The lastest move represents American Brands'third stock split in the last decade. The company split thestock 2-for-1 in 1981 and 1986.</LP><TEXT>   American Brands also declared a dividend of 38.5 cents ashare on the post-split shares, payable Dec. 1 to holders ofrecord Nov. 8. The dividend is equal to 77 cents on eachshare prior to the split, which is nine cents a share, orabout 13%, more than it has been paying.   William J. Alley, chairman and chief executive officer,said American Brands expects another &quot;record year in 1990,&quot;and that the stock split and the dividend increase reflect&quot;the board's continued confidence in the prospects for thecompany.&quot; He didn't elaborate beyond the statement.   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange,American Brands common shares closed at $68 a share, up $1.75   In 1989, the company earned $630.8 million, or $6.51 ashare, up 20% from its previous year, on revenue of $11.92billion. For the first six months of this year, AmericanBrands reported net income of $353.8 million, or $3.62 ashare, up 20%, on revenue of $6.16 billion, compared withyear-earlier net of $292.4 million, or $3.05 a share, onrevenue of $5.99 billion.   The company makes cigarette brands such as Lucky Strikeand Carlton, liquors including Jim Beam whiskey, and Titleistgolf balls. It also provides life insurance through theFranklin group of companies, operates the Wilson Jones officeproducts business, and recently acquired Moen Group Inc., afaucet maker, from Forstmann, Little andamp; Co. for $975 million.</TEXT></DOC>